nice and worm when they get there.

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:02.210
Okay, we're going to brush half of these squares
with some egg wash, and we've just beaten

00:01:02.210 --> 00:01:03.210
an egg here.

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:07.040
And this is later going to act as a glue between
the two squares of pastry.

00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:09.720
So you keep going until half the squares are
covered.

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:15.230
Okay so we have some small pieces of brie
that we've cut up, and we also have some quince

00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:16.260
jelly here.

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:20.500
We'll get one small bit of brie, and we'll
place in the center of one of the pieces of

00:01:20.500 --> 00:01:22.350
pastry that has egg wash.

00:01:22.350 --> 00:01:28.270
Just a small bit of quince jelly here.

00:01:28.270 --> 00:01:31.470
We're going to take one of our squares that
doesn't have the egg wash on it already and

00:01:31.470 --> 00:01:36.890
just gently tug it out, just a little bit
as you can see, so it's slightly bigger than

00:01:36.890 --> 00:01:39.390
the one we're going to place it on top of.

00:01:39.390 --> 00:01:44.640
We're then going to get the egg wash, and
go just around the outsides.

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:48.300
So it's literally like a glue.

00:01:48.300 --> 00:01:52.850
Place it over the top of the brie and quince
jelly.

00:01:52.850 --> 00:01:56.540
And then we're going to take it, and just
squeeze the edges together to seal them.

